RGNAME>Royal Horticultural Society</ORGNAME> at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Wisley</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Surrey"/><GEOG/></PLACE>.<BIBCITS/> </P></EDUCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Marriage</HEADING><FAMILY><CHRONSTRUCT CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" RESP="IMG"><DATE>1 January 1994</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Alice Oswald">Alice Keen</NAME> married <NAME>Peter Oswald</NAME> in the parish chuch at <PLACE><REGION/><SETTLEMENT>Duntisbourne Rouse</SETTLEMENT><GEOG/></PLACE>. The two are the same age, having met in their first year as undergraduates at Oxford.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Times Digital Archive, under Marriage (6 January 1994)" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3Aa8d85257-981c-47e5-8ef7-3c25095bfa02"/><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Armitstead" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3Afeea1f7e-4b37-4f66-925c-4ebb8e96240a"/></BIBCITS> </CHRONPROSE></CHRONSTRUCT><P>He is also a <JOB>writer</JOB>, working in drama. <CHILDREN NUMBER="3">They have three children (two boys and a girl), born between 1996 and 2003.</CHILDREN><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Peerage, under Alice Priscilla Lyle Keen" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3Af8b72982-0a54-4329-bcbe-03377f3e18db"/><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Armitstead" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3Afeea1f7e-4b37-4f66-925c-4ebb8e96240a"/></BIBCITS> </P></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Gardener to Writer</HEADING><OCCUPATION><P>AO took up <JOB>gardening</JOB> as a suitable day job to combine with <JOB REG="writer">writing</JOB>. Her mother's reputation no doubt helped her to secure work on many famous gardens. She apprenticed with the <ORGNAME>National Trust</ORGNAME> at <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Cliveden House">Cliveden</PLACENAME><REGION REG="Berkshire"/><GEOG/></PLACE>, and worked there and at <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Waddesdon Manor">Waddesdon</PLACENAME><REGION REG="Buckinghamshire"/><GEOG/></PLACE> and <PLACE><PLACENAME>Clovelly Court</PLACENAME> in <REGION>Devon</REGION><GEOG/></PLACE>. At the last, where she was employed in 1994, <REMUNERATION>her wages were a hundred and fifty pounds a week and use of a two-room cottage tied to the job</REMUNERATION>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Armitstead" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3Afeea1f7e-4b37-4f66-925c-4ebb8e96240a"/><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Grove, under A Garden path to poetry's prize list (10 January 1997)" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3Aa8d85257-981c-47e5-8ef7-3c25095bfa02"/></BIBCITS> </P></OCCUPATION><OCCUPATION><P>In 2019, rather more than twenty years after giving up professional gardening for writing full-time, AO was elected <JOB>Professor of Poetry</JOB> at <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME>Oxford University</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER>.<BIBCITS/> </P><HEADING>Writer to Professor</HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="PERIOD" RELEVANCE1="SELECTIVE1" RESP="IMG"><DATE>June 2019</DATE><CHRONPROSE>AO was elected by a large majority to the 311-year-old <JOB REG="Professor of Poetry">Chair of Poetry</JOB> at <ORGNAME>Oxford University</ORGNAME>, as the first woman to hold the position.<BIBCITS/> </CHRONPROSE></CHRONSTRUCT><P>This was ten years after the fiasco in which <NAME>Ruth Padel</NAME> was elected, but resigned nine days later in face of controversy over her part in spreading the allegation that one of the other (male) candidates had been accused of sexual harrassment.</P><P>Oswald declared her intention of reaching out from the university to the city and especially to children, of holding extreme poetry events, and of looking at every form of poetry, but particularly the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fugitive airborne forms.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/> </P></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Motherhood, Places, Politics</HEADING><FAMILY><P>When she was pregnant with her first child, Joe, AO and her husband thought they would manage the birth themselves, with a birth pool but without help from anybody like mothers or sisters. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">We thought it would all come naturally. But it didn't.</QUOTE> It was a long labour; Peter had a play in rehearsal; Alice's blood pressue soared, and she ended up in hospital. She then went to stay with her mother while she learned to cope with her baby.<BIBCITS/> </P></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><OTHERLIFEEVENT><P>The year after Joe's birth, AO was living with her husband and baby (like hermits in an eighteenth-century grotto, she said) in a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">grey council-style house</QUOTE> belonging to the <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Dartington</SETTLEMENT> Estate<REGION REG="Devon"/><GEOG REG="England"/></PLACE> near <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Totnes</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION>Devon</REGION><GEOG REG="England"/></PLACE>, an arts and educational foundaiton. She never cleaned the house, she said, during the years that she was working on the poem that made her name, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Dart</TITLE>. She decided to see the dust in corners as evidence of creativity, not sloppiness.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Grove, under A Garden path to poetry's prize list (10 January 1997)" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3Aa8d85257-981c-47e5-8ef7-3c25095bfa02"/><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Johnson, under Why the posh are grubbier (11 June 2013)" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3Aa8d85257-981c-47e5-8ef7-3c25095bfa02"/></BIBCITS> </P></OTHERLIFEEVENT></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><P>AO is not afraid of taking a stand on political issues, broadly considered. In 2011 she withdrew from consideration of the T. S. Eliot Prize in protest against the private investment management firm which was sponsoring the award.<BIBCITS/> </P></POLITICS></DIV1> <HEADING>Writing</HEADING><DIV1><HEADING>Beginnings</HEADING><P><PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">AO later said that a particular night of sleeplessness and terrors made her a writer.</PMOTIVES> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS>She began writing poetry when she was very young, hiding the results under bushes in the garden so that nobody would see them.</PMATERIALCONDITIONS><BIBCITS/> </P></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>First Collection</HEADING><DIV2> <TEXTSCOPE PLACEHOLDER="AO, The Thing in the Gap-Stone Stile, 1996"/> <PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" RESP="IMG"><DATE>21 March 1996</DATE><CHRONPROSE>AO published her first volume of <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poems</TGENRE> (mostly short), calling it <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Thing in the Gap-Stone Stile</TITLE>.<RESEARCHNOTE>HS to KH: There is a missing space between the date tag and the chronprose tag, here and throughout the entry.</RESEARCHNOTE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS/> </CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>A gap-stone stile is a narrow gap purposely left by the maker of a drystone wall, negotiable by two-legged but not four-legged creatures. It therefore gives a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sensation of being between two places, a magical moment.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/> </P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><P><RRESPONSES FORMALITY="INFORMAL" RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO">Twenty years later <NAME>Carol Ann Duffy</NAME> recalled buying this book for her daughter; it helped form her early convinction that Oswald is <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the best UK poet now writing, bar none.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/> </RRESPONSES></P></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>First Success, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Dart</TITLE></HEADING><DIV2> <TEXTSCOPE PLACEHOLDER="AO, Dart, 2002"/> <PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" RESP="SYS"><DATE>8 July 2002</DATE> <CHRONPROSE>The work appeared that made AO's name: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Dart</TITLE> a <TGENRE GENRENAME="TOPOGRAPHICALPOETRY">topographical poem</TGENRE> with a difference, about <TTHEMETOPIC>the <PLACE><REGION>Devon</REGION><GEOG/></PLACE>  <PLACE><REGION>river</REGION><GEOG/></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC> near which she lives.<BIBCITS/> </CHRONPROSE></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>For this poem she spent two years recording the remarks of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">people who know the river,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Oswald, prelims" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3A2cc01676-d1e0-4182-81b8-9372bc8c6d50">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and know it in many different ways.</P></SHORTPROSE><SHORTPROSE><P><TVOICENARRATION>Some of these voices are ruminative: the aged walker with his maps, the anturalist with her notebook. Some are pleasure-bent (swimmers, kayakers, energetic young people having a good time), but many are intent on gleaning a hard living from the river: catching fish or crabs or eels, working the woollen mills, cleaning rooms for the tourists.</TVOICENARRATION> Even the swimmers bring to mind the generations of <TTHEMETOPIC>corpses drowned in the river</TTHEMETOPIC>. There are <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">enmities and violence</TMOTIF>, <TTHEMETOPIC>poachers and bailiffs</TTHEMETOPIC>, not only beating the other boats to the best places, but also <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">if anyone else turns up, break their legs.</QUOTE><RESEARCHNOTE>HS: Quotes checked; page refs uncheckable right now.</RESEARCHNOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Oswald, 41, 42" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3A2cc01676-d1e0-4182-81b8-9372bc8c6d50">41, 42</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </P><P>Unlike other topographical poets, Oswald does not describe landscape or prospect. The sensuously descriptive style of this poem applies to tiny natural details (pole-straight pine woods, / slippy oakwoods),<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3A2cc01676-d1e0-4182-81b8-9372bc8c6d50" REF="Oswald, 9">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> living things (seals <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">all swaddled / and tucked in fat . . . . With their grandmother mouths, with their dog-soft eyes</QUOTE>), <BIBCITS><BIBCIT>Oswald, 48</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and always water, the river itself, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">this jostling procession of waters, / its many strands overclambering one another.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Oswald, 42" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3A2cc01676-d1e0-4182-81b8-9372bc8c6d50">42</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><RESEARCHNOTE>HS: Sources checked; page refs uncheckable right now.</RESEARCHNOTE></QUOTE></P><P><RRESPONSES FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO" RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL"><NAME>David Wheatley</NAME> responded to this poem by establishing it as a landmark in the broadest literary landscape. <PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="LITERARY">He compared Oswald in some detail with <NAME STANDARD="James Joyce">Joyce</NAME> (another writer much possessed by water) </PINFLUENCESHER> He rejoiced at her showing <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">that poetry need not choose between <NAME STANDARD="Ted Hughes">Hughesian</NAME> deep myth and <NAME STANDARD="Philip Larkin">Larkinesque</NAME> social realism,</QUOTE> and pronounced: <QUOTE>She offers, in a word, what too much contemporary poetry forbids itself: ambition.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/> </RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Moew Collections</HEADING><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Woods Etc.</TITLE></HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="PERIOD" RESP="IMG"><DATE>5 May 2005</DATE><CHRONPROSE>AO entitled her next <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poetry</TGENRE> volume <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Woods Etc.</TITLE><BIBCITS/> </CHRONPROSE></CHRONSTRUCT><P>This volume does not aim at the scope and size of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Dart</TITLE>, but collects shorter, self-contained poems equally strong on observation of and sensitivity towards natural objects (including rivers, again, and the moon, another favourite topic) and processes. Even more personal poems, like <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lovesong for Three Children</TITLE>, the poet's concentration remains on her subject rather than her self.<BIBCITS/> </P><P><RRESPONSES FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO" RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL">The reviewer for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Independent</TITLE> found this book less impressive than <TITLE TITLETYPE="MON