" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3A58ab0e1b-e85d-488a-ad1a-656095806929"/><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Winterson" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3A9002eff7-2859-4323-ac29-b8535e659257 "/></BIBCITS> Reviewing it in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times">The Times</TITLE>, she argued that women's poetry differs from men's because poetry is a physical art, reflecting the writer's body. The trouble is, she wrote, <QUOTE>Our literary prejudices have not quite made room for the female as universal.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT>Winterson Times<RESEARCHNOTE>HS to IMG: I've had a hard time tracking down this article because there were no articles by Winterson in the works cited that covered these details. One article I found by Winterson in the Times Digital Archive that touches on these topics is 'It's not facts, it's emotion', (3 Sept, 2005), but the details in that article don't quite match up with the details here, and the article also doesn't contain the quotation that's used here. Could you take a look at the article I found and let me know whether you'd like to use that article and tweak the details here to match, or whether you'd simply like to remove this last bit?</RESEARCHNOTE></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </RRESPONSES></P> <HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Memorial</TITLE></HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="PERIOD" RESP="IMG"><DATE>6 October 2011</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TINTERTEXTUALITY GENDEROFAUTHOR="MAN" INTERTEXTTYPE="ADAPTATION-UPDATE">AO published a <TGENRE>poem </TGENRE>which she calls variously an excavation of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Iliad</TITLE> <TINTERTEXTUALITY GENDEROFAUTHOR="MAN" INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED">and a homage to <NAME>Homer</NAME>: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Memorial</TITLE>.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></TINTERTEXTUALITY></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Blackwell" REF="https://cwrc.ca/islandora/object/orlando%3Adda04f91-a80e-4fe0-bbb4-5e62d5420761"/><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Kel