fa02"/></BIBCITS> </PPERFORMANCE></P><P> <PPERFORMANCE><PPERFORMANCE>AG adapted the text of <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC" REG="AO, Tithonus, 216">Tithonus</TITLE> to fit the music of <NAME>Griselda Sanderson</NAME>, a busker whom she ecnountered playing in the street in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Totnes</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Devon"/><GEOG REG="England"/></PLACE>, on a Sweidsh instrument called a nickel-harpa. She persuaded Sanderson to perform with her at the Literary Festival in <PLACE><PLACENAME>Queen Elizabeth Hall</PLACENAME> on <SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT>'s</PLACE></PPERFORMANCE></PPERFORMANCE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>South Bank</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><PPERFORMANCE><PLACE><REGION REG="Middlesex"/><GEOG REG="England"/></PLACE> on <DATE>9 October 2014</DATE>.<BIBCITS/> </PPERFORMANCE> <RESEARCHNOTE>HS to KH: There are spacing issues around the place tag here and throughout the entry.</RESEARCHNOTE></P><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY>Like <NAME>Alfred Tennyson</NAME>'s poem of the same title seventy years before, this one concerns the <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Tithonus">character</TCHARACTERNAME> in Greek mythology who received the gift of <TTHEMETOPIC>eternal life with no accompanying grant of eternal youth</TTHEMETOPIC>, and who after many years came to long for death.</TINTERTEXTUALITY> <TVOICENARRATION>Oswald's speaker and his surroundings seem to become greyer and fainter as the poem fades towards its end.</TVOICENARRATION></P><P> <NAME REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca//orlando:e391ab5f-567c-4195-9195-6f7886bb5894" STANDARD="Fiona Sampson">Fiona Sampson</NAME> judged that this poem's layout was innovative without being tricksy. The whole collection, she wrote, ebbs and flows, with <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">free verse . . . tightly controlled, so that the breath-phrase from which it is built seems merely natural.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/> It moved <NAME>Dan Chiasson</NAME> to call AO a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">poet whose thoughts are saturated with prior literature</QUOTE> as well as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fundamentall